				<p><span class="style10">POSTER ABSTRACTS </span><br>
				  
				  <br>
				  <a href="2008deMorree.php" class="style18">Next</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
				<a href="2008McNeilA.php" class="style18">Previous</a>
				  <br>
				  
				  <br>
				  
				   <strong><span class="style17">M. Carrie Miceli, PhD and Stan Nelson, MD</span></strong><br>
				  
				   <em>David Geffen School of Medicine at UCLA</em><em></em><br>
				   <br>
				  
				   <img src="images/conference2008/Miceliandnelson.jpg" width="270"><br>
				   <br>
				   <br>
				  
				   <strong>UCLA Muscular Dystrophy Drug Screening and Target Discovery Program: </strong><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong><br>
				  
				  M C Miceli, S Nelson, L Baum, P Cabrera, R. Crosbie, M Moran, P Maurizio, A Pyle, M Spencer. <br>
                  <br>
                  The development and implementation of cellular reporter assays which model processes relevant to muscular dystrophies enables high throughput screens (HTS) of small molecule libraries for the identification of lead compounds with the capacity to modulate dystrophy relevant processes.  Such compounds have tremendous potential as probes for understanding normal and pathologic muscle cell biology and in the development of novel therapeutics for muscular dystrophies.  A promising approach to the rapid identification of novel therapeutics involves the large scale testing of known drug compounds in specific miniaturized cellular assays.  We describe the ongoing efforts at UCLA to identify chemical modifiers of physiologic processes relevant to muscular dystrophy.  Some targets are highly specific to Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy (DMD) mutations, while others are more generally relevant to potentially any muscular dystrophy.  The program is currently targeting 4 different processes, the modulation of which are known or likely to show therapeutic benefit.  These include: 1) assays designed to detect enhancers of membrane stability through upregulation of surface glycosylaton (WFA/laminin binding) and/or sarcospan expression; 2) assays designed to identify enhancers of dystrophin exon skipping; and 3) assays designed to identify negative regulators of fibrosis through down-regulation of osteopontin or fibrosis reporters; and 4) assays designed to drive pluripotent stem cells to myoblast differentiation.  Most assays are developed within C2C12 myoblasts or myotubes and subsequently validated on primary mdx mouse myoblasts/tubes.  However, a panel of human DMD patient derived cell myoblast lines are currently being developed by reprogramming fibroblasts for further compound validation and pre-clinical assessment and for the stem cell screen.  Here we present current data on the detection of modifiers of antisense mediated dystrophin gene exon skipping and upregulators of WFA/laminin binding.  These developed assays were demonstrated sufficiently robust for HTS and novel compound detection, and were then employed to screen off patent FDA approved drug compound (Prestwick Library, 1120 compounds) and know biologically active molecule (BioMol, 600 compounds) libraries.  The WFA/laminin binding screen has lead to the identification of a lead compound which we have characterized as an upregulator of GalNac transferase mRNA expression, restoration of DCG components and ligand (agrin) protein expression, and WFA and laminin binding.  The exon skipping screen has lead to the identification of 15 lead compounds, a subset of which have been validated in secondary molecular screens and characterized with regard to their ability to facilitate mouse exon 23 and off target non-dystrophin exons and for their ability to synergize with AON to facilitate targeted skipping.  Our exon skipping screen is extended by a collaborative parallel screen being performed at the Genomics Institute of Novartis in which almost 1 million compounds have been screened.  Through this collaboration, a link to drug development through the pharmaceutical industry has been established.  The chemical modifier screens are complemented by a proposed collaborative effort to use genome-wide association analysis of disease severity in DMD boys to identify genetic modifiers in order to elucidate novel therapeutic targets. </p>
